+**Choose execution strategy:**
+After user approves spec, present three options:
+- **Sequential** (default): single agent, step by step — writing-plans then executing-plans
+- **Parallel subagents**: independent tasks in parallel, no inter-agent communication — writing-plans then subagent-driven-development
+- **Agent teams**: coordinated team with shared task list and inter-agent messaging — writing-plans then coordinated team via agent teams
+
+**Agent type assignments** (parallel/teams only):
+Present a table mapping each planned task to a suggested agent type based on language/domain:
+
+| Domain / Language | Agent Type |
+|---|---|
+| Rust | systems-programming:rust-pro |
+| Go | systems-programming:golang-pro |
+| Nix / general | general-purpose |
+
+User reviews and overrides. Final assignments saved to spec under `## Agent Assignments`.
+
+**Agent teams review protocol** (teams only):
+When agent teams strategy is chosen, the team-lead enforces two-stage review gates:
+1. **Spec compliance review**: reviewer reads actual code against task requirements
+2. **Code quality review** (only after spec compliance passes): checks decomposition, patterns, quality
+3. **Final holistic review**: cross-stream review for consistency and integration
+
+**Transition to implementation:**
+- Invoke the writing-plans skill with agent assignments to create a detailed implementation plan
+- Then execute with the chosen strategy
+- Do NOT invoke any other skill. writing-plans is the next step after brainstorming.
+
+## Humanize All Non-Code Prose
+
+Apply the `humanizer` skill to all non-code text throughout brainstorming. This includes:
+
+- **Design presentations** (approach proposals, design walkthroughs)
+- **Spec documents** (the written design doc saved to disk)
+- **Plan prose** (goal descriptions, architecture summaries, task descriptions)
+- **Questions and explanations** (clarifying questions, approach reasoning)
+
+**Does NOT apply to:** code blocks, file paths, commands, configuration snippets, structured data (tables, checklists).
+
+**How to apply:** Strip AI-isms inline as you write — don't produce slop then clean it up. Watch for:
+- Significance inflation ("pivotal", "crucial", "vital role", "testament")
+- Promotional language ("vibrant", "groundbreaking", "seamless")
+- Copula avoidance ("serves as", "stands as" instead of "is")
+- Superficial -ing phrases ("highlighting", "underscoring", "fostering")
+- Rule-of-three lists, negative parallelisms ("not just X, but Y")
+- Filler ("in order to", "it is important to note")
+- Sycophantic openers ("Great question!", "Absolutely!")
+- Generic positive conclusions ("the future looks bright")
+- Em dash overuse, excessive boldface, emoji decoration

-- Invoke the writing-plans skill to create a detailed implementation plan
-- Do NOT invoke any other skill. writing-plans is the next step.
+Write like a person talking to another person. Vary sentence rhythm. Have opinions. Be specific.

